posts.name: hrench
posts.cooked:
Our “elevator” travels to L4 from 42" height in less than one second.  We have a unique elevator…instead of complicated roller-bearings and strings, we simply have two aluminum box-sections that slide inside one another, lifted by rack-and-pinions made of steel 40-size sprockets on both sides. Lifted by one Neo with 12:1 at the floor of the robot, driven by chain.

Our focus has been on simplicity and light-weight.  Our coral actuator is one ‘pokey thing’ and one wheel, less than a foot long.   The whole robot is 102 lbs now.  i’m guessing the whole up-and-down part weighs less than five pounds. It moves 27 inches.

The most productive match I’ve counted, we placed 14 coral, two in auto.

Because its lowest position is the human player station, we’re having a tough time retrofitting floor-pick-up, but we’re working on it. {168406A8-1CA8-4B52-9347-EBD8B91A29FD} 671×885 64.7 KB

posts.name: Garrison
posts.cooked:
We’re down to about 0.6 seconds for our full extension to L4. Running 2 Vortexes at ~7.44:1 with a 22T # 25 sprocket with a cascade setup. The initial stage moves ~30" to L4. We have a 10lb constant force spring on the carriage to help offset most of the weight.

At our first competition we didn’t have the CF spring and were geared at 12:1 and had a max extension time around 0.9 seconds. The CF spring helped significantly; we only saw a small speed improvement with the gear change alone.
Try using amb calc to calculate the ratio of the elevator. It sounds like your elevator is overgeared and isn’t making full use of the motors.

posts.name: Sean Lavery
posts.cooked:
PixL:

For us we have neos with a 16:1 reduction.

How is your elevator strung? What size pulleys or sprockets are you using? How far is your desired elevator travel? How many stages is your elevator? How many Neos are you using? What are your current limits? How heavy are each of your elevator stages?

All of these pieces of information (and more) can impact the performance of your system as a whole.

posts.name: Sean Lavery
posts.cooked: My apologies, I should have been a bit more clear that my question was intended to be a bit rhetorical. My point was that the system behavior is influenced by a large number of factors beyond just motors, gear ratios, and settings in code. Other teams’ settings aren’t necessarily going to be right for you if your elevator is heavier, or uses a different method of driving its second stage, or has a different pulley diameter than yours. (Etc)

posts.name: Chase Eid
posts.cooked: Yeah, I know. I wasn’t asking how to get it faster, but rather seeing if others with a similar setup to ours were getting faster speeds with the same gearbox. It seems that we have pretty much hit the limit for speed at our current parameters and will be switching to a lower gearbox. I should have clarified that in the post as well.

posts.name: John Hascall (he)
posts.cooked: Not sure of our ratio, but with 2 Krakens it’s fast enough that before adding ballast, the whole robot could do a wee bunny hop if we ran it full speed all the way up.

posts.name: Tori Dell
posts.cooked: 0.8 seconds from bottom to L4 for our 3-stage cascading elevator running 2 Krakens with 4:1 sport gearboxes. 22T # 25 sproket for first stage, then steel cable for the following stages, and also a 6 lb constant force spring on the final stage. Total travel distance of end effector is 69". It definitely helps that we can slightly ram the end effector against the top to not worry too much about bounce or slowing down when going to L4.

Not quite apples to apples, but our “elevator” goes from stowed to L4 in somewhere between 0.46-0.5 seconds (estimated from frame count at 24 fps). We’ve got a composite roller system similar to what a few teams have done with FTC and 6377 did with Shrinky Dink, but we ran two rollers on a 7:1 reduction if memory serves.

posts.name: coderkevin
posts.cooked:
Our “elevator” is made of two 2-stage extension arms, so we can’t compare 1:1 with you. However I drive this concept pretty hard with my teams:

All robot mechanism motions should be geared for a theoretical 0.5 second movement. This will usually allow for 1 second movements in the real world where inertia and mechanical resistance apply.

If we follow this advice in your gearing calculations, we usually get the results we want and movements are snappy. Remember, 1/2 of a second matters when you’re trying for 16 cycles a match (that’s 8 seconds combined!)
